{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"68d7b3d1-0297-45b7-99d2-79263c4b0f97","content":"macOS automatically generates crash reports — no extra tools needed:\n\n**Crash reports (`.ips` files):**\n```\n~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n```\nLook for a file named after your process (e.g., `MyApp-2026-05-12-xxxxxx.ips`). These contain the native backtrace, signal info, and loaded images.\n\n**Core dumps (optional):**\n```bash\n# Enable core dumps before running your app\nulimit -c unlimited\n# After crash, look in:\n/cores/\n```\n\n**Tips:**\n- The `.ips` crash report is usually sufficient for NativeAOT — it includes the full native stack trace.\n- If you have the `apple-crash-symbolication` skill or `atos` + dSYM symbols, you can symbolicate the `.ips` to get function names and line numbers.\n- Core dumps in `/cores/` can be opened with `lldb` for deeper analysis.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"66f7d95a-21e7-41e2-8da5-fd2fdad8ff52","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET app on macOS, specifically when `createdump` isn't available. This is a knowledge question — I don't need to search the codebase. Let me answer directly.\n\nOn macOS, when a process crashes, the OS automatically generates a crash report (`.ips` file) in `~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/` (for user processes) or `/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/` (for system processes). These are plain-text/JSON crash logs that contain the backtrace.\n\n\nSince NativeAOT doesn't include `createdump`, I should mention that macOS handles this automatically through its crash reporting system. I can also note that core dumps are available if the user enables them with `ulimit -c unlimited`, which places them in `/cores/`.","outputTokens":480,"requestId":"1B85:B86C3:DB3D86:FA93F8:6A028690"},"id":"c6bb0966-7e0b-4ec6-a25d-16cd2bf40fe7","timestamp":"2026-05-12T01:47:08.476Z","parentId":"130d1836-6784-4b60-832d-883e84b2c8ec"}
